            , No. 12, John-street, Hampstead-road;" I gave him eight sovereigns, and 12s. in change, and then he bought two waistcoats.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290219-160-person1509">
                  GRIFFITH 
                  FOLKES
               <interp inst="t18290219-160-person1509" type="surname" value="FOLKES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290219-160-person1509" type="given" value="GRIFFITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290219-160-person1509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a draper, and live in Little Russell-street, Drury-lane. On the 31st of December, between five and six o'clock in the evening, the prisoner came to my shop, alone; he bought some things, but not in my presence - I did not serve him, but Adams called me forward, and said he had brought a 10l. Farnham note; I told the prisoner it was a late hour to pass so large a note, he being a countryman - he said,</p>
               <p>"If you don't like to change it I can't have the goods which I want - I want to buy a gown for my wife;" I called one of my shopmen forward to serve him; I made inquiry about it, and agreed to Adams' taking it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290219-160-person1510">
